## Detailed Findings

---

**Finding #1**
- **Severity:** 🔴 Critical
- **Rule:** AP-02 — Global singleton registry (Anti-Pattern §11)
- **Location:** [commands/base.py](file:///x:/agent_cli/agent_cli/commands/base.py#L147), line 147
- **Offending Code:**
  ```python
  _DEFAULT_REGISTRY = CommandRegistry()
  ```
- **Why it violates the guideline:**
  Section 8.1 and Anti-Pattern table both explicitly warn: *"Never use a global singleton registry"* because *"state bleeds between tests; tight coupling."* `_DEFAULT_REGISTRY` is a module-level global that collects `@command` decorator registrations at import time. While it is later "absorbed" into a fresh instance at bootstrap, the original global persists in module scope and can be imported/accessed by any module, creating hidden coupling.
- **Suggested Fix:**
  ```python
  # Option 1: Use a deferred registration list (not a registry)
  _PENDING_COMMANDS: List[CommandDef] = []

  def command(...):
      def decorator(func):
          _PENDING_COMMANDS.append(CommandDef(..., handler=func))
          return func
      return decorator

  # In bootstrap: iterate _PENDING_COMMANDS to populate injected CommandRegistry
  ```
- **Notes:** The [absorb()](file:///x:/agent_cli/agent_cli/commands/base.py#106-110) pattern is a reasonable workaround for decorator-time registration, but the global [CommandRegistry](file:///x:/agent_cli/agent_cli/commands/base.py#88-141) instance still supports `.get()`, `.all()`, etc., and is used directly in Finding #7.

---

**Finding #2**
- **Severity:** 🔴 Critical
- **Rule:** R-7.8 — Implement a freeze phase (§7.8); R-7.5 — Validate at registration time (§7.5)
- **Location:** [providers/manager.py](file:///x:/agent_cli/agent_cli/providers/manager.py#L37-L44), lines 37–44
- **Offending Code:**
  ```python
  ADAPTER_TYPES: Dict[str, Type[BaseLLMProvider]] = {
      "openai": OpenAIProvider,
      "azure": AzureProvider,
      "anthropic": AnthropicProvider,
      "google": GoogleProvider,
      "ollama": OllamaProvider,
      "openai_compatible": OpenAICompatibleProvider,
  }
  ```
- **Why it violates the guideline:**
  This is a plain mutable dictionary at module scope — it has no freeze phase (§7.8), no validation (§7.5), and no protection against runtime mutation. The guideline states: *"Freezing prevents accidental runtime mutations and enables whole-registry validation."* Any code can mutate `ADAPTER_TYPES` at runtime (e.g., `ADAPTER_TYPES["custom"] = MyProvider`), introducing unpredictable behavior.
- **Suggested Fix:**
  ```python
  # Use types.MappingProxyType for an immutable view
  from types import MappingProxyType

  _ADAPTER_TYPES_MUTABLE = {
      "openai": OpenAIProvider,
      ...
  }
  ADAPTER_TYPES: Mapping[str, Type[BaseLLMProvider]] = MappingProxyType(_ADAPTER_TYPES_MUTABLE)
  ```
- **Notes:** Alternatively, wrap in a proper registry class with freeze support.

---

**Findings #3–#6 (Systemic — No Freeze Phase)**
- **Severity:** 🔴 Critical
- **Rule:** R-7.8 — Implement a freeze phase
- **Locations:**
  - [tools/registry.py](file:///x:/agent_cli/agent_cli/tools/registry.py), [ToolRegistry](file:///x:/agent_cli/agent_cli/tools/registry.py#25-110) (lines 25–109)
  - [agent/registry.py](file:///x:/agent_cli/agent_cli/agent/registry.py), [AgentRegistry](file:///x:/agent_cli/agent_cli/agent/registry.py#10-38) (lines 10–37)
  - [commands/base.py](file:///x:/agent_cli/agent_cli/commands/base.py), [CommandRegistry](file:///x:/agent_cli/agent_cli/commands/base.py#88-141) (lines 88–141)
  - [agent/session_registry.py](file:///x:/agent_cli/agent_cli/agent/session_registry.py), [SessionAgentRegistry](file:///x:/agent_cli/agent_cli/agent/session_registry.py#29-104) (lines 29–104)
- **Why it violates the guideline:**
  None of these registries implement the three-phase lifecycle: **Populate → Validate → Freeze**. After bootstrap populates them, they remain open for mutation. The guideline prescribes: *"OPEN → FROZEN → runtime. Freezing prevents accidental runtime mutations."* The [DataRegistry](file:///x:/agent_cli/agent_cli/core/registry.py#26-735) is the only component that is effectively read-only after construction (it loads JSON in [__init__](file:///x:/agent_cli/agent_cli/core/events/event_bus.py#126-135)), but even it doesn't expose a formal freeze API.
- **Suggested Fix:**
  Add a `_frozen` flag and `freeze()` method to each registry, raising on post-freeze mutations. Call `freeze()` at the end of [create_app()](file:///x:/agent_cli/agent_cli/core/bootstrap.py#319-644).
- **Notes:** [SessionAgentRegistry](file:///x:/agent_cli/agent_cli/agent/session_registry.py#29-104) is a special case — it is designed for runtime mutation (add/remove/switch agents). A read-only freeze may not apply fully here, but a "startup-complete" phase gate would still be useful.

---

**Finding #7**
- **Severity:** 🟡 Warning
- **Rule:** AP-02 — Global singleton registry (Anti-Pattern §11); R-5 — Registry vs. Service Locator (§5)
- **Location:** [commands/handlers/core.py](file:///x:/agent_cli/agent_cli/commands/handlers/core.py#L37-L40), lines 37–40
- **Offending Code:**
  ```python
  from agent_cli.commands.base import _DEFAULT_REGISTRY
  registry = _DEFAULT_REGISTRY
  ```
- **Why it violates the guideline:**
  The `/help` command handler directly imports the global `_DEFAULT_REGISTRY` instead of using the injected [CommandRegistry](file:///x:/agent_cli/agent_cli/commands/base.py#88-141) from [AppContext](file:///x:/agent_cli/agent_cli/core/bootstrap.py#69-312). This is a service locator anti-pattern: *"Consumers pull from registry directly, hiding dependencies."* The handler has access to [CommandContext](file:///x:/agent_cli/agent_cli/commands/base.py#66-81) which could carry the live registry.
- **Suggested Fix:**
  ```python
  async def cmd_help(args: List[str], ctx: CommandContext) -> CommandResult:
      registry = ctx.app_context.command_registry  # Use injected registry
      ...
  ```

---

**Finding #8**
- **Severity:** 🟡 Warning
- **Rule:** AP-02 — Global singleton registry
- **Location:** [core/logging.py](file:///x:/agent_cli/agent_cli/core/logging.py#L415-L445), lines 415–445
- **Offending Code:**
  ```python
  _OBSERVABILITY: Optional[ObservabilityManager] = None

  def configure_observability(...) -> ObservabilityManager:
      global _OBSERVABILITY
      ...

  def get_observability() -> Optional[ObservabilityManager]:
      return _OBSERVABILITY
  ```
- **Why it violates the guideline:**
  This is a global singleton pattern. The [ObservabilityManager](file:///x:/agent_cli/agent_cli/core/logging.py#166-405) is stored in a module-level global and accessed via [get_observability()](file:///x:/agent_cli/agent_cli/core/logging.py#443-446) from handlers like [cmd_cost](file:///x:/agent_cli/agent_cli/commands/handlers/core.py#133-160) and [cmd_debug](file:///x:/agent_cli/agent_cli/commands/handlers/core.py#345-385). The guideline warns this *"couples tightly"* and *"state bleeds between tests."* Note: [AppContext](file:///x:/agent_cli/agent_cli/core/bootstrap.py#69-312) already holds the [observability](file:///x:/agent_cli/agent_cli/core/logging.py#443-446) field, so the global is redundant.
- **Suggested Fix:**
  Access observability through `ctx.app_context.observability` instead of [get_observability()](file:///x:/agent_cli/agent_cli/core/logging.py#443-446). Remove the module-level global.

---

**Finding #9**
- **Severity:** 🟡 Warning
- **Rule:** R-7.5 — Validate at registration time
- **Location:** [tools/registry.py](file:///x:/agent_cli/agent_cli/tools/registry.py#L38-L43), lines 38–43
- **Offending Code:**
  ```python
  def register(self, tool: BaseTool) -> None:
      if tool.name in self._tools:
          raise ValueError(f"Tool '{tool.name}' is already registered.")
      self._tools[tool.name] = tool
  ```
- **Why it violates the guideline:**
  While duplicate-name detection is present (good), there is no type/interface validation. The guideline reference implementation validates that the factory is callable. For [ToolRegistry](file:///x:/agent_cli/agent_cli/tools/registry.py#25-110), it should verify the tool conforms to `BaseTool` interface — e.g., has a valid [name](file:///x:/agent_cli/agent_cli/agent/registry.py#36-38), `description`, implements `get_json_schema()`, etc.
- **Suggested Fix:**
  ```python
  def register(self, tool: BaseTool) -> None:
      if not isinstance(tool, BaseTool):
          raise TypeError(f"Expected BaseTool, got {type(tool).__name__}")
      if not tool.name or not tool.name.strip():
          raise ValueError("Tool must have a non-empty name")
      if tool.name in self._tools:
          raise ValueError(f"Tool '{tool.name}' is already registered.")
      self._tools[tool.name] = tool
  ```

---

**Finding #10**
- **Severity:** 🟡 Warning
- **Rule:** R-7.5 — Validate at registration time
- **Location:** [agent/registry.py](file:///x:/agent_cli/agent_cli/agent/registry.py#L21-L25), lines 21–25
- **Offending Code:**
  ```python
  def register(self, agent: BaseAgent) -> None:
      name = agent.name
      if name in self._agents:
          raise ValueError(f"Agent '{name}' is already registered.")
      self._agents[name] = agent
  ```
- **Why it violates the guideline:**
  Same issue as Finding #9. Only duplicate-name checking is done. No validation that [agent](file:///x:/agent_cli/agent_cli/agent/session_registry.py#102-104) is a proper `BaseAgent` instance, has a non-empty name, or has required attributes.
- **Suggested Fix:** Add `isinstance` and name validation checks.

---

**Finding #11**
- **Severity:** 🟡 Warning
- **Rule:** AP-07 — Silent overwrites (Anti-Pattern §11)
- **Location:** [commands/base.py](file:///x:/agent_cli/agent_cli/commands/base.py#L101-L104), lines 101–104
- **Offending Code:**
  ```python
  def register(self, cmd: CommandDef) -> None:
      self._registry[cmd.name.lower()] = cmd
      logger.debug("Registered command: /%s", cmd.name)
  ```
- **Why it violates the guideline:**
  The `CommandRegistry.register()` silently overwrites any existing command with the same name. The guideline states: *"Later registrations silently replace earlier ones"* is an anti-pattern. The recommended default is *"Error on duplicate keys."* While the [absorb()](file:///x:/agent_cli/agent_cli/commands/base.py#106-110) flow intentionally merges, the base [register()](file:///x:/agent_cli/agent_cli/tools/registry.py#38-44) method should guard against accidental overwrites.
- **Suggested Fix:**
  ```python
  def register(self, cmd: CommandDef, *, override: bool = False) -> None:
      key = cmd.name.lower()
      if key in self._registry and not override:
          raise ValueError(f"Command '/{cmd.name}' is already registered.")
      self._registry[key] = cmd
  ```

---

**Finding #12**
- **Severity:** 🟡 Warning
- **Rule:** R-7.5 — Validate at registration time
- **Location:** [providers/manager.py](file:///x:/agent_cli/agent_cli/providers/manager.py#L37-L44), lines 37–44
- **Why it violates the guideline:**
  The `ADAPTER_TYPES` dict has no validation that values are actually subclasses of `BaseLLMProvider` or that keys are non-empty strings. The validation only happens lazily at resolution time (line 187–191), which violates the principle: *"Catch bad registrations early rather than failing at runtime."*
- **Suggested Fix:** Add a startup assertion in `ProviderManager.__init__` that validates all adapter types.

---

**Finding #13**
- **Severity:** 🟡 Warning
- **Rule:** R-7.9 — Make it observable
- **Location:** [core/registry.py](file:///x:/agent_cli/agent_cli/core/registry.py), entire class (lines 26–735)
- **Why it violates the guideline:**
  [DataRegistry](file:///x:/agent_cli/agent_cli/core/registry.py#26-735) has no logging of any kind — no logging on offering registration, model spec resolution, or capability cache operations. The guideline recommends: *"Log every registration with key, source, and timestamp. Expose a debug dump of the full registry state. Emit metrics on resolution frequency and failures."*
- **Suggested Fix:** Add `logging.getLogger(__name__)` and log at `DEBUG` level during [_load_offerings()](file:///x:/agent_cli/agent_cli/core/registry.py#343-412), [resolve_model_spec()](file:///x:/agent_cli/agent_cli/core/registry.py#145-160), and cache operations.

---

**Finding #14**
- **Severity:** 🟡 Warning
- **Rule:** AP-01 — Hardcoded if/switch dispatch (Anti-Pattern §2, §11)
- **Location:** [core/registry.py](file:///x:/agent_cli/agent_cli/core/registry.py#L650-L658), lines 650–658
- **Offending Code:**
  ```python
  @staticmethod
  def _declared_support(spec: CapabilitySpec, capability_name: str) -> bool:
      if capability_name == "native_tools":
          return bool(spec.native_tools.supported)
      if capability_name == "effort":
          return bool(spec.effort.supported)
      if capability_name == "web_search":
          return bool(spec.web_search.supported)
      return False
  ```
- **Why it violates the guideline:**
  This is a textbook if/switch dispatch. Adding a new capability requires modifying this method. The guideline explicitly targets this pattern: *"The if/switch block is the data, just written as code."*
- **Suggested Fix:**
  ```python
  _CAPABILITY_ACCESSORS = {
      "native_tools": lambda spec: spec.native_tools.supported,
      "effort": lambda spec: spec.effort.supported,
      "web_search": lambda spec: spec.web_search.supported,
  }

  @staticmethod
  def _declared_support(spec: CapabilitySpec, capability_name: str) -> bool:
      accessor = DataRegistry._CAPABILITY_ACCESSORS.get(capability_name)
      return bool(accessor(spec)) if accessor else False
  ```

---

**Findings #15–#19** are 🔵 Info-level discovery/discoverability gaps. Each registry is missing some subset of tag-based filtering, key listing, or general discovery APIs. These are not critical but limit runtime inspectability.

---

**Finding #20**
- **Severity:** 🔵 Info
- **Rule:** R-7.2 — Store factories, not instances (by default)
- **Location:** [core/bootstrap.py](file:///x:/agent_cli/agent_cli/core/bootstrap.py#L692-L721), lines 705–714
- **Offending Code:**
  ```python
  registry.register(ReadFileTool(workspace))
  registry.register(WriteFileTool(workspace))
  # ... (all tools registered as instances)
  ```
- **Why it violates the guideline:**
  Tools are registered as pre-instantiated instances rather than factories. The guideline says *"Factory (callable): creates a new object on each resolve — safer for stateful things"* and recommends factories as the default. However, tools appear to be effectively stateless (they delegate to workspace), so instances are acceptable here.
- **Notes:** This is a minor style deviation. Using factories would enable per-resolve configuration but may be unnecessary given the stateless design.

---

## Systemic Issues

| Pattern | Rule Violated | Files Affected | Recommended Action |
|---------|--------------|----------------|--------------------|
| No freeze phase in any registry | R-7.8 | [tools/registry.py](file:///x:/agent_cli/agent_cli/tools/registry.py), [agent/registry.py](file:///x:/agent_cli/agent_cli/agent/registry.py), [commands/base.py](file:///x:/agent_cli/agent_cli/commands/base.py), [agent/session_registry.py](file:///x:/agent_cli/agent_cli/agent/session_registry.py), [providers/manager.py](file:///x:/agent_cli/agent_cli/providers/manager.py) (5 files) | Add `_frozen` flag and `freeze()` method to a shared `BaseRegistry` mixin; call `freeze()` at end of [create_app()](file:///x:/agent_cli/agent_cli/core/bootstrap.py#319-644) |
| No validate phase in any registry | R-7.8 | Same 5 files | Add [validate()](file:///x:/agent_cli/agent_cli/core/registry.py#246-272) method that checks internal consistency before `freeze()` |
| Minimal registration-time validation | R-7.5 | [tools/registry.py](file:///x:/agent_cli/agent_cli/tools/registry.py), [agent/registry.py](file:///x:/agent_cli/agent_cli/agent/registry.py), [commands/base.py](file:///x:/agent_cli/agent_cli/commands/base.py) (3 files) | Add type checks (`isinstance`), non-empty key checks, and interface conformance assertions in all [register()](file:///x:/agent_cli/agent_cli/tools/registry.py#38-44) methods |
| Global singleton pattern for cross-cutting concerns | AP-02 | [commands/base.py](file:///x:/agent_cli/agent_cli/commands/base.py) (`_DEFAULT_REGISTRY`), [core/logging.py](file:///x:/agent_cli/agent_cli/core/logging.py) (`_OBSERVABILITY`) | Eliminate globals; use [AppContext](file:///x:/agent_cli/agent_cli/core/bootstrap.py#69-312) as the single source of truth |
| No observability/logging in registries | R-7.9 | [core/registry.py](file:///x:/agent_cli/agent_cli/core/registry.py), [agent/registry.py](file:///x:/agent_cli/agent_cli/agent/registry.py), [agent/session_registry.py](file:///x:/agent_cli/agent_cli/agent/session_registry.py) (3 files) | Add structured logging at registration, resolution, and cache events |

